main event: A white, round object, the size of a dim star's length, was observed slowly rising in Suquamish, Washington on September 2, 1956.
interesting points: The object was observed for over 3 hours and 15 minutes.
The report includes 3 photographs of the object.
The analysis indicates the sighting was caused by an observation of the planet Mars.
The conclusion lists possible explanations as: Astronomical - Mars, Probably Balloon, Insufficient Data for Evaluation, Unknown.

The report also mentions a separate sighting of a white circular object by two USAF Washington Air National Guard pilots on September 22, 1955. The object was observed for 15-20 minutes and displayed erratic flight patterns and maneuvers.
sighted object: white, round object the size of a dim star's length
